Why cant I rename it?

option.name: displayContent
option.value:
The error occurs because the `name` property of the `Project` object in Gradle is read-only, meaning it cannot be modified once the project is created. The `name` property is set when the project instance is created and reflects the project's directory name unless explicitly defined in the settings file.
If you need a different way to handle the name or work with identifiers, you should consider setting a custom property or using different project logic. Renaming the project should be done in the `settings.gradle` or `settings.gradle.kts` file, not within the `build.gradle` file.
Here's what you can do:
### Renaming in `settings.gradle`
If you want to rename the project, you should do so in the `settings.gradle` or `settings.gradle.kts` file, like this:
#### `settings.gradle` ```gradle rootProject.name = 'newNameForRootProject' include ':deployment' project(':deployment').name = 'newNameForDeployment' ```
#### `settings.gradle.kts` ```kotlin rootProject.name = "newNameForRootProject" include(":deployment") project(":deployment").name = "newNameForDeployment" ```
Make sure this is defined in the `settings.gradle` or `settings.gradle.kts` file at the root of your project.
### Using a Custom Property If renaming the project itself is not the appropriate action but you need to refer to the project with a different identifier in your `build.gradle` file, you can define a custom property:
#### `build.gradle` ```gradle ext { customProjectName = 'customDeploymentName' }
// usage println "Custom Project Name: $customProjectName" ```
#### `build.gradle.kts` ```kotlin extra["customProjectName"] = "customDeploymentName"
// usage println("Custom Project Name: ${extra["customProjectName"]}") ```
This way, you can work with `customProjectName` in your build script without altering the read-only `name` property.
